Hey Sandeep!
Please let me know whatever it is you would like help on. i'll try my best to help :slightly_smiling_face:
Just so you know, i'm currently working remotely for MPC so I can not respond to messages during the day, but after 18:30 each day I will be available!

Hi Michael :slightly_smiling_face:
Great to meet you I'm a 3D VFX student at Escape Studios on my 3rd year and at the moment I'm somewhat of a generalist but I love creature modelling, grooming and creating digidouble. At the moment I need the most help on is grooming and Look dev because its such a complex thing to do. I use Xgen Description and Houdini as the softwares to do groom. Look dev wise I struggle with that a lot because its not something I've found enjoyable.

Ok cool, how long is your course? Are you in your final year?

I should be able to help for those topics, I was a groom TD at MPC for over 2 years. For Lookdev its something I have spent a lot of time learning (I started learning Lookdev in 2014).
Sculpting is pretty fun too, havent done it a lot over the last 3 years but I did spend a lot of time in zbrush over the last 8 years :slightly_smiling_face:

You've done a lot :astonished:
well I'm in my final year for bachelors but I have one more year for my Masters
Sounds great man, seems like you're enjoying it too since you're using free time to be on this site :slightly_smiling_face:
Thats the digital Emily model right?
yup
A classmate of mine recommended using her
If I can ask how did you get into Visual Effects ?
I love that model, its a great tool for learning. have you read through the wiki human project? theres a lot of information about her and the process they used to make her
Sure, you want to know how I got from uni to my first job or do you want to know more about my education?
I haven't read too much on her but, I did reasearch on FACS because I saw the making of relicts movie,
I would like to know both

<http://www.wikihuman.org/>
Theres the site, its pretty interesting :slightly_smiling_face:

in terms of my education I started with a games design course at college back in 2012. that was a two year course and covered concepting through to setting up renders in mental ray (Back when mental ray was still popular, RIP). At that point my main focus was on modelling, I also joined a few forums back then like polycount which taught me a lot of tricks.

When I finished that course I went to Bournemouth university (2014). While there I spent the first year mainly focused on modelling but I did start to learn basics of lookdev, comp, texturing and some more advanced rendering (still mental ray). in the second year is when i started to focus on lookdev and comp (but i still did a lot of sculpting and animating at that point). that stayed pretty much the same until the end of university except I also started learning groom.

During uni I also launched my website (<http://mikecauchiart.com|mikecauchiart.com>) on which I made free tutorials and I also wrote some articles for 3D aryist magazine. during the summer holidays for 2015 and 2016 I competed in the BFX fesitival in Bournemouth which taught me a lot about the whole pipeline and just forcing things to work :smile:


By the end of uni I had 5 years of learning VFX, games and animation. However for me what was most important was networking, I managed to get an interview with MPC just because I knew some of the leads. technically I never applied to work at MPC but I sent out applications to a lot of places and got a lot of rejections too XD
My first job was as a groom artist for lion king. Networking is incredibly important for sure

Wow thats really cool, for me I never knew about vfx until my final year of college and its just been a steep learning curve from day one. In regards to networking I've always found that daunting because its like you're going to an event wanting to get contacts and jobs, knowing that the recruiters know thats what you want and it just feels like a strange place to be in

Luckily there are many ways to network. This for example, as time goes and and we talk more i may be able to help you get in touch with recruiters or leads that I know :slightly_smiling_face:
I found that facebook groups like level up and ten thousand hours are great. If you post frequently you will naturally have a few people comments on multiple posts, thats a great way to get in touch.

I'm going to head off for the night, let me know what you would like to learn first and we cant start tomorrow :slightly_smiling_face:
Heres what I need to know:
• Do you have a plan for what you want to learn and it what order
• Do you prefer to learn one skill at a time, or do you prefer to learn a few things at the same time
• How often do you want to send me work and do you want me to set goals for you
For now if you want I can give feedback on the images you sent me earlier once I am back online tomorrow :slightly_smiling_face:
see ya!
